question:
Equilateral triangle $DEF$ is inscribed in equilateral triangle $ABC$ as shown with $\overline{ED}\perp\overline{BC}.$ What is the ratio of the area of $\triangle DEF$ to the area of $\triangle
ABC$? [asy]
import olympiad; import geometry; size(100); defaultpen(linewidth(0.8));
draw(dir(90)--dir(210)--(dir(-30))--cycle);
pair[] inters = intersectionpoints(Circle(origin,1/sqrt(3)),dir(90)--dir(210)--(dir(-30))--cycle);
inters[5] = dir(210) + ((dir(-30) - dir(210))/3);
draw(inters[0]--inters[2]--inters[5]--cycle);
draw(rightanglemark(inters[2],inters[5],dir(210),4));
dot("$A$",dir(90),N);
dot("$C$",dir(210),W);
dot("$B$",dir(-30),E);
dot("$F$",inters[0],E);
dot("$E$",inters[2],W);
dot("$D$",inters[5],S);
[/asy]

solution:
Since $\triangle CDE$ has a right angle at $D$ and $\angle C = 60^\circ,$ we can let $CD = x,$ $DE = x\sqrt{3},$ and $CE = 2x$ for some positive $x.$
[asy]
import olympiad; import geometry; size(100); defaultpen(linewidth(0.8));
draw(dir(90)--dir(210)--(dir(-30))--cycle);
pair[] inters = intersectionpoints(Circle(origin,1/sqrt(3)),dir(90)--dir(210)--(dir(-30))--cycle);
inters[5] = dir(210) + ((dir(-30) - dir(210))/3);
draw(inters[0]--inters[2]--inters[5]--cycle);
draw(rightanglemark(inters[2],inters[5],dir(210),4));
dot("$A$",dir(90),N);
dot("$C$",dir(210),W);
dot("$B$",dir(-30),E);
dot("$F$",inters[0],E);
dot("$E$",inters[2],W);
dot("$D$",inters[5],S);
label("$x$",dir(210)--inters[5],S);
label("$2x$",dir(210)--inters[2],W);
label("$x$",inters[2]--dir(90),W);
[/asy]Note that $\triangle AEF \cong \triangle CDE,$ because $\angle AEF = 180^\circ - \angle DEF - \angle CED = 180^\circ - 60^\circ - 30^\circ = 90^\circ,$ $\angle EAF = 60^\circ,$ and $EF = DE.$ Then $AE = CD = x,$ so the side length of $\triangle ABC$ is $AC = AE + EC = 2x + x = 3x.$

Finally, the ratio of the areas of the triangles is the square of the ratio of the side lengths: $$\left(\frac{DE}{AC}\right)^2=\left(\frac{x\sqrt{3}}{3x}\right)^2=\boxed{\frac 13}.$$

question:
In the figure, square $WXYZ$ has a diagonal of 12 units. Point $A$ is a midpoint of segment $WX$, segment $AB$ is perpendicular to segment $AC$ and $AB = AC.$ What is the length of segment $BC$? [asy]
import olympiad; size(150); defaultpen(linewidth(0.8));

draw(unitsquare);
draw((2,0)--(0.5,0)--(0.5,1.5)--cycle);
label("$W$",(0,0),W); label("$X$",(1,0),S); label("$Y$",(1,1),E); label("$Z$",(0,1),W);
label("$A$",(0.5,0),S); label("$B$",(2,0),E); label("$C$",(0.5,1.5),N);
[/asy]

solution:
Triangles WXY and BXY are isosceles triangles that have a leg in common, so they are congruent.  Therefore segment $YB$ is equal to a diagonal of square $WXYZ$, so its length is 12 units. By adding point $D$, as shown, we can see that triangles $CDY$ and $YXB$ are similar to triangle $CAB$. This also means that triangle $CDY$ is similar to triangle $YXB$. Since the sides of two similar triangles are related by a constant factor, and we can see that the length of $DY$ is 1/2 the length of $XB$, we know that the length of $CY$ must be $(1/2)(12) = 6$ units. Thus, the length of CB is $12 + 6 = \boxed{18\text{ units}}$. [asy]
import olympiad; size(150); defaultpen(linewidth(0.8));
draw(unitsquare);
draw((2,0)--(0.5,0)--(0.5,1.5)--cycle);
label("$W$",(0,0),W); label("$X$",(1,0),S); label("$Y$",(1,1),E); label("$Z$",(0,1),W);
label("$A$",(0.5,0),S); label("$B$",(2,0),E); label("$C$",(0.5,1.5),N);
label("$D$",(0.5,1),NW);
[/asy]

