label("$y=\frac{1}{2}x-2$",(8,2),NE);
label("$y=-2x+8$",(8,-8),SE);
[/asy]

solution:
We first determine where the lines $y=-2x+8$ and $y = \frac{1}{2}x-2$ cross the line $x=-2.$

For the line $y=-2x+8,$ when $x=-2,$ $y=-2(-2)+8=12,$ so the point of intersection is $(-2,12).$

For the line $y=\frac{1}{2}x-2,$ when $x=-2,$ $y=\frac{1}{2}(-2)-2=-3,$ so the point of intersection is $(-2,-3).$

